== Main Events == ;Torch Throwing Participants aim torches at a "beehive" (a straw-filled basket) mounted atop a tall pole, spinning and throwing the torches to ignite it. Once burned, the pole is shaken to release the remains. The tradition is similar to the {{ill|Karigane Festival|ja|かりがね祭り|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Karigane Festival|qq=}} held in [[:en:Fuji, Shizuoka|Fuji, Shizuoka]]. Before World War II, this event spanned three nights (August 14–16) and used split cedar logs tied with bamboo hoops. Modern torches are made from reused cloth soaked in waste oil or kerosene and secured with wire. ;Giant Torches Old tōba (wooden memorial plaques) from local temples are stacked to create large torches. These are lit around 7 PM following sutra chanting by monks. ;One Hundred and Eight Fires Symbolizing the cleansing of humanity's 108 earthly desires (bonnō), the ritual also serves as a memorial for the dead and a pest control measure to drive away rice planthopper pests (unja). Cone-shaped bonfires are placed along both banks of the [[:en:Fuji River|Fuji River]], covering approximately 2 km. All 108 fires are lit simultaneously at 8 PM following a siren. ;Fireworks Following the lighting of the 108 fires, a fireworks display featuring 3,000 shells, including two-foot diameter shells, illuminates the sky. ;Additional Activities The main venue on the Mutsumiai side features events such as karaoke contests and food stalls. However, due to financial constraints in Nanbu Town, the scale of the festival has been reduced in recent years.
